04283nam a22005535i 9780231546379DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018043470  a97802315463797 a10.7312/chio185882doi  a(DE-B1597)526811  a(OCoLC)1100429547  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aPN1995.7 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a378.712211 aChion, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAudio-Vision: Sound on Screen /cMichel Chion. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b64 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword (1994) -- tPreface -- tPart I: The Audiovisual Contract -- t1. Projections Of Sound On Image -- t2. The Three Listening Modes -- t3. Lines And Points: Horizontal And Vertical Perspectives On Audiovisual Relations -- t4. The Audiovisual Scene -- t5. The Real And The Rendered -- t6. Phantom Audio- Vision; Or, The Audio- Divisual -- tPart II: Beyond Sounds And Images -- t7. Sound Film Worthy Of The Name -- t8. Toward An Audio- Logo- Visual Poetics -- t9. An Introduction To Audiovisual Analysis -- tGlossary -- tChronology: Landmarks of the Sound Film -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMichel Chion’s landmark Audio-Vision has exerted significant influence on our understanding of sound-image relations since its original publication in 1994. Chion argues that sound film qualitatively produces a new form of perception. Sound in audiovisual media does not merely complement images. Instead, the two channels together engage audio-vision, a special mode of perception that transforms both seeing and hearing. We don’t see images and hear sounds separately—we audio-view a trans-sensory whole.In this updated and expanded edition, Chion considers many additional examples from recent world cinema and formulates new questions for the contemporary media environment. He takes into account the evolving role of audio-vision in different theatrical environments, considering its significance for music videos, video art, commercial television, and the internet, as well as conventional cinema. Chion explores how multitrack digital sound enables astonishing detail, extending the space of the action and changing practices of scene construction. He demonstrates that speech is central to film and television and shows why “audio-logo-visual” is a more accurate term than “audiovisual.” Audio-Vision shows us that sound is driving the creation of a sensory cinema.This edition includes a glossary of terms, a chronology of several hundred significant films, and the original foreword by sound designer, editor, and Oscar honoree Walter Murch.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMotion picturesxSound effects. 0aSound motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aGorbman, Claudia.1 aMurch, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chio1858840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231546379.jpg  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles